File: South Africa's Minister of Health Zweli Mkhize addresses a media. JOHANNESBURG - As officials across the world scramble to deal with the coronavirus outbreak, South Africa has confirmed six new cases, bringing the total to 13. eNCA’s Slindelo Masikane explores the details and concerns in SA and around the globe. Courtesy #DStv403 Health Minister Zweli Mkhize confirmed six new cases of COVID-19 in the country, outside of the group of 10 people who returned from Italy. READ: Coronavirus: How big, how bad, and what to look out for According to a statement released by the Health Department, four cases are in Gauteng, one is in KwaZulu-Natal and one in the Western Cape. Gauteng patients KwaZulu-Natal patient In KZN, an infected person is a 40-year-old man who had travelled to Portugal. He returned on 7 March. Western Cape patient A 36-year-old male tested positive. He travelled to multiple countries including Germany, Austria, Switzerland and Turkey. He returned to South Africa on 9 March. All the patients have been advised. Those who are symptomatic have started receiving treatment. READ: What you need to know about coronavirus Some of the patients are already in the hospital while some, specifically those who are asymptomatic, are in self-quarantine. Contact tracing has started for all these cases. To date, 645 tests have been conducted. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday